A co-end is a categorical construction that generalizes the notion of a tensor product of functors. Given a functor \(T: \mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}} \times \mathcal{C} \to \mathcal{D}\), the co-end \(\int^{c \in \mathcal{C}} T(c,c)\) is defined as the coequalizer of the diagram \(\coprod_{f: c \to c'} T(c',c) \rightrightarrows \coprod_{c \in \mathcal{C}} T(c,c)\), where the two maps are induced by the action of \(T\) on the morphism \(f\) in the first and second arguments respectively. Equivalently, it is the universal dinatural cocone over \(T\), meaning it receives a dinatural transformation from \(T(-,-)\) that is initial among all such transformations. Co-ends arise naturally in diverse contexts including the construction of geometric realizations of simplicial objects, the definition of the tensor product of modules over a noncommutative ring (via the Yoneda lemma), and in the abstract formulation of Kan extensions.